  "texts": [
    "3 It might be the case that practical rationality is a merely accidental feature of human cognition, and that it can be fully accounted for in terms of biological function, causation and information processing, while still being symptomatic of the particular blend of these elements manifested by practically rational cognitive agents.",
    "We might then be justified in characterising cognitive agency as shaped by such norms and goals even though at some lower level of explanation, we expect them to disappear from the picture of the world given by science.",
    "That is, paraphrasing Fodor (1987, p. 97), we might think that \"if [cognition] is real, it must be really something else.\"",
    "4 On the other hand, we might think that the norm-guided teleology exhibited by practically rational agents is a robustly real, 'emergent' feature of any world with creatures like us in it.",
    "However these questions are resolved, we could still ask about the minimal conditions for such a world -a world of cognising creatures and rational agents."
  ],
